05649nam a22009135i 9783110648096DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106480967 a10.1515/97831106480962doi  a(DE-B1597)513087  a(OCoLC)1206402097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB753.R44bN63 2021 7aPHI0220002bisacsh04a297.20922231 aNoble, Michael-Sebastian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophising the Occult :bAvicennan Psychology and 'The Hidden Secret' of Fakhr al-Dīn al-Rāzī /cMichael-Sebastian Noble. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 299 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History and Culture of the Middle East ;v3500tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tChapter 1. al-Sirr al-maktūm -- tChapter 2. Sabians -- tChapter 3. Eight Sabian Doctrines -- tChapter 4. The General Physics of Talismans -- tChapter 5. Making Talismans -- tChapter 6. Sabian Spiritual Discipline and Avicennan Cognition Theory -- tChapter 7. Sabian Perfected Man and the Avicennan Theory of Prophethood -- tChapter 8. Occult Epistemology -- tChapter 9. An Alternative Account of Astral Visions -- tChapter 10. A Clarification -- tChapter 11. al-Maṭālib 8 and the New Islamic Soteriology -- tChapter 12. Concluding Remarks -- tAppendix -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas it mere encyclopedism that motivated Fakhr al-Dīn al-Rāzī (d.1210), one of the most influential Islamic theologians of the twelfth century, to theorize on astral magic – or was there a deeper purpose? One of his earliest works was The Hidden Secret (‘al-Sirr al-Maktūm’), a magisterial study of the ‘craft’ which harnessed spiritual discipline and natural philosophy to establish noetic connection with the celestial souls to work wonders here on earth. The initiate’s preceptor is a personal celestial spirit, ‘the perfect nature’ which represents the ontological origin of his soul. This volume will be the first study of The Hidden Secret and its theory of astral magic, which synthesized the naturalistic account of prophethood constructed by Avicenna (d.1037), with the perfect nature doctrine as conceived by Abū’l-Barakāt (d.1165). Shedding light on one of the most complex thinkers of the post-Avicennan period, it will show how al-Rāzī’s early theorizing on the craft contributed to his formulation of prophethood with which his career culminated. Representing the nexus between philosophy, theology and magic, it will be of interest to all those interested in Islamic intellectual history and occultism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aMagie. 4aProphetentum. 4aSabier. 4aSoteriologie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aSabians.  amagic.  aprophethood.  asoteriology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2021z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831106446160 cprintz978311064457940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311064809